    body: "A VA disability rating is the percentage the Department of Veterans Affairs assigns to a service-connected condition, in 10 percent steps from 0 to 100. The rating sets your tax-free monthly check. As of May 2026, a single veteran rated at 30 percent receives $537.42 each month, while a single veteran rated at 100 percent receives $4,044.91. If you are a senior veteran whose hearing has worsened, whose back pain has grown sharper, or whose PTSD now keeps you from sleeping, you may qualify for a higher rating. The VA calls this a rating increase claim. Filing one does not put your existing rating at risk in most cases, because the law protects ratings that have been in place for five years or longer from being reduced without strong medical evidence.\n\nAbout 5.6 million American veterans receive monthly VA disability compensation, and roughly one in three are age 65 or older. Many conditions get worse with age, especially musculoskeletal injuries, hearing loss, tinnitus, sleep apnea, cardiovascular disease tied to Agent Orange or burn pits, and mental health conditions like PTSD or depression. The VA expects veterans to file for rating increases when symptoms worsen, and the agency processes about 1.4 million claims a year. The average rating increase claim takes about 130 days in 2026, though some are decided in under 90 days.\n\nBefore you file, take an honest inventory of how your condition has changed. Pull your most recent VA medical records. Compare them to records from the year you were last rated. Look for new diagnoses, new medications, new restrictions on what you can do, and new doctor notes that describe worse symptoms. The stronger your medical evidence, the faster your claim will move and the more likely you are to win an increase. You do not need a lawyer to file. You can file online at va.gov, by paper using VA Form 21-526EZ, or with free help from an accredited Veterans Service Officer at the American Legion, VFW, DAV, or your county Veterans Affairs office.\n\nOne tip that helps many senior veterans: ask your doctor for a Disability Benefits Questionnaire, often called a DBQ. These are specific VA forms that doctors fill out to document how a condition affects you. A complete DBQ written by your treating physician, attached to your claim, often moves the case forward faster than any other piece of evidence. DBQs are free, available on va.gov, and many private doctors will fill them out at no charge during a normal appointment if you bring the form with you.",
