    difficulty: "Intermediate",
    body: "The Department of Veterans Affairs Caregiver Support Program supports the family members and friends who care for disabled veterans at home. The program has two parts. The Program of Comprehensive Assistance for Family Caregivers, called PCAFC, pays a tax-free monthly stipend to a designated family caregiver and provides ongoing training, mental health counseling, respite care, and travel reimbursement. The Program of General Caregiver Support Services, called PGCSS, is open to caregivers of any enrolled veteran and offers free training, support groups, peer mentoring, and a 24-hour caregiver hotline at 1-855-260-3274.\n\nAs of May 2026, PCAFC monthly stipend amounts in most areas of the country are about $2,750 per month for a Tier 1 primary caregiver and about $4,400 per month for a Tier 2 primary caregiver. Tier 1 is for veterans who need help with some daily activities, and Tier 2 is for veterans who cannot live without near-constant supervision. The exact amount depends on the local hourly home health aide wage published by the federal Bureau of Labor Statistics for your zip code. The stipend is paid by direct deposit to the caregiver's bank account, not to the veteran. The caregiver does not have to be a spouse; an adult child, parent, sibling, grandchild, or close friend can serve as the primary family caregiver.\n\nIn 2022, Congress expanded PCAFC to include veterans from every era of service. Before 2022, the program was limited to post-9/11 veterans. Today, a Vietnam veteran, a Korean War veteran, or any other senior veteran can have a family caregiver enrolled. To qualify, the veteran must have a single or combined service-connected disability rating of 70 percent or higher, must need at least six months of personal care because of a service-connected condition, and must require help with at least three activities of daily living or have a serious cognitive condition like Alzheimer's, dementia, or severe traumatic brain injury.\n\nThe PCAFC application process is detailed but doable in a few weeks with steady effort. Free help is available from every VA medical center's Caregiver Support Coordinator, a paid VA employee whose only job is to walk caregivers through the program. There is no fee to apply and no fee for any part of the program. The benefit is in addition to any VA disability compensation the veteran already receives; the caregiver stipend does not reduce the veteran's check. The stipend is also tax-free under federal law, though some states may treat it as income; check with a tax preparer if you live in California, New York, or another state with broader income definitions.",
