    difficulty: "Intermediate",
    body: "A VA presumptive condition is an illness the Department of Veterans Affairs assumes was caused by military service if the veteran served in a specific place or time. The veteran does not have to prove the link between the illness and the service; the VA accepts the link by law. The PACT Act, signed in August 2022, expanded the presumptive list more than any law in fifty years. It added 23 new conditions tied to airborne hazards like burn pits, expanded Agent Orange coverage for Vietnam-era veterans, and added presumptions for veterans exposed to contaminated water at Camp Lejeune from 1953 to 1987.\n\nFor a senior veteran, presumptive coverage matters because many cancers and chronic conditions show up decades after exposure. A Vietnam veteran sprayed with Agent Orange in 1969 might develop prostate cancer in 2026 at age 80. A Gulf War veteran exposed to burn pits in 1991 might develop a rare lung condition in 2026 at age 70. Without the presumption, the veteran would have to prove with medical evidence that the cancer was caused by service, which is nearly impossible decades later. With the presumption, the VA accepts the cause as service-connected by federal law, and the veteran can receive monthly disability compensation, free VA health care for the condition, and survivor benefits for the family.\n\nThe PACT Act covers veterans who served in many places. Agent Orange presumptions cover Vietnam and surrounding areas from 1962 to 1975, Thailand bases, Korean DMZ from 1967 to 1971, and certain US testing sites. Burn pit presumptions cover post-9/11 veterans who served in Iraq, Afghanistan, Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, Qatar, Oman, UAE, Yemen, Djibouti, Egypt, Jordan, Lebanon, Syria, and Uzbekistan, plus Gulf War veterans from 1990 to 1991 in Bahrain, Iraq, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Somalia, and UAE. Camp Lejeune water contamination covers anyone who lived or worked at Camp Lejeune, North Carolina, for at least 30 days between August 1953 and December 1987, including family members.\n\nThe full list of presumptive conditions is long and updated regularly. Major Agent Orange conditions include prostate cancer, bladder cancer, hypertension, ischemic heart disease, Parkinson's disease, diabetes type 2, and several others. Major burn pit and airborne hazard conditions include brain cancer, lung cancer, throat cancer, kidney cancer, melanoma, asthma, chronic bronchitis, and many more. Major Camp Lejeune conditions include leukemia, kidney cancer, liver cancer, bladder cancer, multiple myeloma, non-Hodgkin lymphoma, and Parkinson's disease. The full list is at va.gov/disability/eligibility/hazardous-materials-exposure/ and is reviewed by the VA every year.",
