    difficulty: "Beginner",
    body: "Adaptive sports are athletic activities changed to fit people with disabilities. A wheelchair basketball game, a hand-cycle road race, a chair-yoga class, or a guided fishing trip for veterans with low vision are all adaptive sports. The Department of Veterans Affairs runs a national Adaptive Sports and Arts Program that funds more than 100 adaptive sports clinics, camps, and weekly programs across the United States every year. For senior veterans with service-connected or non-service-connected disabilities, adaptive sports can improve balance, build strength, sharpen mental health, and create lasting friendships with other veterans who understand the experience.\n\nResearch from the VA Office of Patient Care Services shows that veterans who join an adaptive sports program report less depression, less chronic pain, better sleep, and stronger overall well-being. For senior veterans, the benefits are even greater. Regular movement of any kind reduces the risk of falls, slows cognitive decline, and keeps independence longer. The VA Adaptive Sports Program is free for enrolled veterans; the VA covers equipment, instruction, and often travel and lodging to clinics. Many programs are run in partnership with non-profits like Disabled Sports USA, Disabled American Veterans, the National Veterans Wheelchair Games, the National Veterans Golden Age Games, and Paralyzed Veterans of America.\n\nThe range of adaptive sports is wide. Year-round options include wheelchair basketball, swimming, cycling, golf, archery, fishing, kayaking, boccia, sled hockey, sit-volleyball, table tennis, equestrian, sailing, and shooting. Seasonal options include snow skiing, snowshoeing, snowboarding, water-skiing, scuba diving, and surfing. Mental wellness options include adaptive yoga, tai chi, qigong, and chair-based fitness classes. Almost every sport played by able-bodied athletes has an adaptive version, and the VA program has at least one chapter near most veterans.\n\nTwo flagship VA events stand out. The National Veterans Wheelchair Games, held every summer, is the world's largest annual wheelchair sports event with about 600 veteran athletes competing in 22 sports. The National Veterans Golden Age Games, held every spring, is for veterans age 55 and older and welcomes about 800 senior veterans for a week of competition in sports ranging from swimming to shuffleboard. The VA funds travel, lodging, meals, and equipment for qualified veterans at both events. Beyond these national games, local VA medical centers host weekly and monthly adaptive programs that any enrolled veteran can join, often within a 30-minute drive of home.",
